<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,310,536,562]" box="[189,310,536,562]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,536,562]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,536,562]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1398,583,680]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
“Test elongate, uniserial; ovoid to fusiform proloculus may be up to twice the length of the first chamber; later chambers usually, but not always separated by long narrow necks; aperture terminal, at end of a long, narrow neck, radiate bars join at center giving petalloid effect.” (
<bibRefCitation author="Hayward B. W. &amp; Kawagata S. &amp; Sabaa A. &amp; Grenfell H. &amp; Van Kerckhoven L. &amp; Johnson K. &amp; Thomas E." box="[1016,1316,654,680]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="408" refId="ref63648" refString="Hayward B. W., Kawagata S., Sabaa A., Grenfell H., Van Kerckhoven L., Johnson K. &amp; Thomas E. 2012. The last global extinction (Mid-Pleistocene) of deep-sea benthic foraminifera (Chrysalogoniidae, Ellipsoidinidae, Glandulonodosariidae, Plectofrondiculariidae, Pleursostomellidae, Stilostomellidae), their Late Cretaceous-Cenozoic history and taxonomy. Cushman Foundation for Foraminiferal Research Special Publication 43: 408." type="journal article" year="2012">
Hayward 
<emphasis box="[1131,1190,654,680]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">et al.</emphasis>
2012: 139
</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
